text:
I‚Äôve had stitches before, and these are my experiences with them:

1. They are very itchy, but don‚Äôt scratch it
2. You will get a raised, red bump for a long time after the stitches are taken out
3. When you do get the stitches taken out, it won‚Äôt hurt. The worst it will be is minor pain with a tug
4. If it‚Äôs on your foot, it will be hard to put socks on (trust me)
And lastly 5. You will most likely have to put salt water on the wound until you get the stitches taken out, to prevent infection.

text: I used to be a wood worker, and got a nasty oak splinter embedded in the palm of my right hand. It shattered under the skin and there were two large pieces left in my hand, and I was unable to reach them. I sat in my car after work trying in vain to dig them out with a sterile pin, but it was no use. A few days later I had a red welt the size of a plum on my hand, and it felt a burning pain constantly. I rubbed some polysporin on it, and when the swelling went down, I could see one of the pieces. I removed it, but the one ahead of it was still deep inside, and I was shaking with pain. A couple days later, the second piece worked it‚Äôs way to the surface, and I removed it. It took another week for my hand to heal up, and it left me with a weird round scar on my palm.

text: Ex nurse here. Most shots are given into the muscle (intramuscular) or just under the skin (subcutaneous).  Areas are picked to avoid injecting into the vein, not the place shown in this video, such as the upper arm, or thigh.  If you need an injection into the vein (intravenous) a cannula is normally inserted and the medication injected into the cannula. The cannula can then be left in place for other iv injections. Or for a drip for example. However, if you need a blood test, access to a vein is needed. Veins are closer to the surface and can often be seen or felt so it is less likely to accidentally hit an artery. I‚Äôve never seen that happen in 30 years. If you don‚Äôt get the needle in correctly like this video shows, blood will leak into the tissues and cause a bruise.  That is what is being spoken about in this video. A bruise. Nothing to worry about.
author: @Spiklething

text: Phlebotomist here! Just wanted to clarify that a clinician would not "give you a shot" in your antecubital fossa (the area where your arm bends) or in any other region with major blood vessels. This demonstration is actually of what can occur during a blood draw (though the needle would be at a shallower angle than was depicted in the video). Otherwise cool video! Hematoma (aka bruising) is a potential side effect of getting blood drawn, but completely harmless!

text:
To everyone commenting saying this unlocked a new fear, this is unfortunately common and happens with everyone once in a while. Your vein can roll or go out of place due to different factors like dehydration and lack of sleep. Not to mention everyone comes with different veins and some are called ‚Äúhard to extract‚Äù, because their veins are either too fragile, thin, or deep seated beneath the skin. Rest assured that health workers are trained to do their job and collection of your blood is a must to do the tests.

The bruising is called ‚Äúhematoma‚Äù, it isn‚Äôt deadly and it doesn‚Äôt really hurt you. To some people commenting badly that it‚Äôs all about money, try to consider the situation from a different point of view.

text:
I‚Äôm a medical laboratory scientist, and we called this Hematoma, it usually happen when extracting blood in median vein (which shown here) and the needle pass through vein or the vein itself rupture (because not all veins are thick, usually depends on the person and current status in health). The typical remedy includes pressing down the site of puncture to stop the bleeding and applying ice pack to site for 3-5 minutes to avoid bruises.

This situation is prone to happen in people with deprived health condition, people with Pulmonary tuberculosis, cancer, HIV patient and so on.

It‚Äôs not life threatening nor can pose health issues, it‚Äôs just that the site would not be available for another blood collection until the bruises (hematoma) subsides.

ps. We typically advise the patient not to bend his/her arm after collection to avoid bruising even after successful extraction.

text: Paramedic here. A few things, no one gives shots directly into a vein. The needle goes in your shoulder, ass, or even stomach fat in some instances (at a steep angle, we ain't just shoving a needle into your guts, quarter inch at most). Medicines given via IM (intramuscular) injection go into muscles, not veins. The only scenario in which a vein can become infiltrated, or punctured through-and-through, is when inserting an IV into your arm or hand. It does hurt, but it's more of a mild burn and heals relatively quickly. It's essentially an internal bruise. Thanks for visiting my Ted Talk.

text: It's called a saw stop, and they are good for educational places, but they can be touchy. If the wood has a high moisture content, it will trigger the saw stop. Best thing to do is always act like there is no safety and proceed with caution. Newer saw stops have gotten better about moisture in wood which is good. Lots of people have kept their fingers thanks to them. If your saw stop activates, it needs to be replaced, and the blade should be replaced as well. Even if the blade looks undamaged.

text: Another reason to not do this on purpose: it breaks the saw and depending on the type, the stopping mechanism, if you set it off. All saw stopping mechanisms like these have a high chance of damaging the saw blade. Some saw stopping mechanisms rely on an explosive charge that basically breaks the whole thing and drops the blade down into the table, and can only go off once, then you'd have to open the whole thing up and fix everything and replace the charge if you want to get it back up and working with the saw stop. The kind in this video uses a block of aluminum and a spring, which is resettable, but not necessarily as reliable as the explosive charge one, due to the fact that it's relying on an aluminum block to stop a speeding saw, and doesn't drop the saw down into the table.

text:
I really like how this works.

Bees are relatively peaceful insects. They know that their stingers are suicidal moves, thus they usually never attack you.
The only 2 contexts in which they attack you are either if you are a "threat" to their hive (e.g. you get too close, or y'know just smack it with a stick, stuff like that) or if you actively try to attack them.

And their only response is to attack you back. Of course, they don't know we aren't gonna die by their stings, so the only thing they do is sacrifice their lives to kill the threat.
Truly an honourful insect.

text:
For Those Wondering:

Imagine lying back in a dentist‚Äôs chair, the drill whirring toward your mouth‚Äîand there‚Äôs no anesthesia. That was reality for dental patients before the mid-1800s. Tooth drilling without numbing agents was a brutal, painful experience. Dentists used hand-cranked drills or early foot-powered models that were slow, loud, and often heated up from friction‚Äîliterally burning your nerves as they ground away decay.

Patients were expected to grip the chair, scream, or even be physically restrained. There was no Novocaine, no laughing gas‚Äîjust grit, courage, and maybe a shot of whiskey. The pain was so intense that people often avoided dentists altogether, allowing infections and rot to spread, sometimes leading to deadly conditions like sepsis.

Fun Fact: The first successful use of anesthesia in dentistry was in 1846, using ether gas, which quickly changed everything. By the early 1900s, dental anesthesia became standard, finally making visits to the dentist a little less terrifying‚Äîand a lot less painful.

text:
I used to live off a channel of Granbury lake and we had gar there. I'm not experienced at fishing at all, but when I got off work in the morning I would go out there and fish for gar, just because they were so fun to try and catch. I caught a few but of course I was never able to reel them in. I'm sure I didn't have strong enough fishing line, and of course not enough experience. But I would get them close enough to maybe get them with a net, so I bought one of those, and I swear as long as I had that net by me I wouldn't catch a thing, as if they knew.

Then one day I caught a catfish, which I was able to easily reel in. But being inexperienced and a bit stupid it didn't occur to me that there wouldn't be enough oxygen in a small container of water. I put it in a small Styrofoam cooler until my husband came home because I didn't know how to clean fish, but the next time I checked on it it was dead.
author: @ProfessionallySingle

text:
The Alligator Gar fish is a remarkable creature that can be found in the waters of Houston, Texas. This unique fish is known for its long, sharp teeth and armored scales, making it stand out in the aquatic world. Despite its fearsome appearance, the Alligator Gar plays an important role in maintaining the balance of the ecosystem by preying on smaller fish and controlling their population. Its presence is crucial for the health of the waterways in Houston.

While the Alligator Gar may seem intimidating, it is actually a fascinating species that is worth learning more about. With its ability to grow over eight feet long and weigh hundreds of pounds, this fish is a true giant of the waters. It is also a resilient creature that has adapted to survive in various habitats, showcasing its ability to thrive in different environments. The Alligator Gar's unique characteristics make it a valuable and intriguing part of Houston's natural biodiversity.

Despite being a lesser-known species, the Alligator Gar holds a special place in the hearts of Houston residents who appreciate the diversity of wildlife in their city. Conservation efforts are being made to protect and preserve the population of Alligator Gar, recognizing its significance in the local ecosystem. As more people become aware of this hidden gem of Houston, the Alligator Gar is sure to receive the recognition it deserves as one of the city's best kept secrets in terms of its unique and important role in the aquatic world.

text: This video is not entirely true.  As a former dairy maintenance professional I can tell you the dimples are for volume control.  The jugs are made by a process called blow molding, which can lead to an imprecise size due to many variable factors.  Those jugs are filled by volume, "to full," so if the internal volume of the jug is off, the amount of milk sold will be wrong.  Those dimples are created by pucks screwed into the mold cavity, and so the volume can be adjusted on each batch of jugs by changing the size of pucks.

text:
Milk jugs often have a dimple or indentation on one side near the bottom for a couple of reasons:

1. Structural Integrity: The dimple in milk jugs serves a structural purpose. It helps prevent the jug from collapsing or distorting when the milk is being poured. The dimple acts as a reinforcement, adding strength and stability to the jug, allowing it to withstand the pressure exerted by the liquid inside.

2. Improved Grip: The dimple also enhances the grip on the jug while pouring. It provides a natural thumb rest, allowing for better control and stability when handling and pouring milk. This feature helps prevent slippage and provides a more comfortable and secure grip for the user.

3. Controlled Flow: The dimple can help in achieving a smoother and controlled pour. It acts as a sort of spout or channel, guiding the milk flow and reducing the likelihood of spills or splashes.

It's important to note that not all milk jugs have a dimple, as different manufacturers may have different designs. However, the presence of a dimple is a common feature in many milk jugs and serves functional purposes as described above.

text:
Dentist here. I'll clarify why some people say root canals hurt while others say it's practically pain free. More often then not it has to do with the state of the nerve in the tooth before having the procedure done. When exposed to bacteria, the nerve and blood supply will swell (just like anywhere else in the body). The swelling occurs in a tight enclosed hard structure (the tooth and the bone). The tissue wants to expand, but it can't so it builds a lot of pressure.

When you get numbed up, typically you're numbing certain types of nerve fibers. One of the last types of nerve fibers that can get numb are pressure sensing nerves. So, if the tooth has been experiencing a lot of pressure it is hard to get numb, and it hurts to do a root canal on it, even with a lot of anesthetic.

In addition, if there is an infection present, the infected tissue becomes pretty acidic. The local anesthetic has epinephrine in it, which is also acidic. The similar properties tend to repell each other.

Some ways to help reduce the pain would be to take an antibiotic beforehand to calm down the infection and reduce the inflammation. You can also split the root canal treatment into multiple appointments where the first appointment would be to directly access the center of the tooth and apply some medicine directly onto the pulp to allow it to become alleviated. Then you'd seal up the tooth with a temporary filling, and set another appointment to finish the root canal treatment after the tooth has calmed down.

If the nerve has become necrotic, and is already dead, it no longer transmits any impulses. This is when a root canal can be nearly pain free. Sometimes a root canal is performed before the nerve gets too irritated, and it can be relatively easier to get numbed as well.

I've had nerve removals and canal cleaning done many times. I hadn't seen a video of this until now but this is what I imagined was happening from what it felt like.

Scary at first, you get used to it. It's not painful, only uncomfortable at some moments. If it's painful, let your dentist know.

If your dentist recommends anesthesia but you're afraid of needles - please, get anesthesia. The needle and feat combined will hurt you less than a canal cleaning without anesthesia.

Also, don't fret if your teeth are having issues. It's not necessarily bad oral hygiene. You may just have lost the genetic lottery.

This is just my personal experience.

text:
It's important to note that a can alone is unlikely to cause significant issues. However, there are a few scenarios in which debris like a can could potentially interfere with a car's brakes:

1. **Physical Obstruction**: If a can were to somehow get lodged in the brakes, such as between the brake rotor and brake caliper, it could prevent proper brake function. This might happen if the can is being compressed or crushed and ends up in a critical area of the braking system.

2. **Fluid Contamination**: If a can is damaged and leaks contents that could be corrosive or that might contaminate brake fluid, it could theoretically impair the brake system's function. However, this would require the can to be positioned in such a way that its contents could mix with the brake fluid.

3. **Puncturing Brake Lines**: If a can were to strike the brake lines or even some other critical component of the braking system while driving, it could potentially damage the braking systems, leading to brake failure.

4. **Driver Distraction**: In a more abstract sense, if a driver were to be distracted by a can in the roadway, it could potentially lead to an inability to stop in time or a collision.

In general, regular maintenance and checks by a professional can help ensure that a car's braking system remains functional and free of obstructions.

text:
For those who didn‚Äôt understand:



The Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor is a fifth-generation, single-seat, twin-engine, all-weather stealth tactical fighter aircraft developed for the United States Air Force (USAF). The F-22 is considered one of the most advanced fighter jets in the world, boasting cutting-edge technology, exceptional maneuverability, and unparalleled stealth capabilities.

Design and Development

The F-22 program began in the 1980s as a response to the USAF's need for a next-generation air superiority fighter. Lockheed Martin (then Lockheed) was awarded the contract in 1991, and the first F-22 prototype made its maiden flight in 1997. The aircraft entered service in 2005.

Components

1. Airframe: The F-22's airframe is made of advanced composite materials, including carbon fiber reinforced polymers (CFRP) and titanium alloys. The airframe is designed to provide exceptional strength, durability, and stealth capabilities.
2. Engines: The F-22 is powered by two Pratt & Whitney F119-PW-100 turbofan engines, each producing 35,000 pounds of thrust. The engines feature advanced compressor and turbine technology, providing exceptional power and efficiency.
3. Avionics: The F-22's avionics system is highly advanced, featuring a sophisticated radar system, advanced sensors, and a highly integrated computer system. The aircraft's avionics are designed to provide exceptional situational awareness, targeting capabilities, and communication systems.
4. Radar System: The F-22's radar system is the Northrop Grumman AN/APG-77 active electronically scanned array (AESA) radar. This system provides exceptional range, resolution, and targeting capabilities, allowing the F-22 to detect and engage multiple targets simultaneously.
5. Stealth Capabilities: The F-22's stealth capabilities are designed to reduce its radar cross-section, making it difficult to detect and engage. The aircraft's stealth features include radar-absorbent materials, curved surfaces, and internal carriage of missiles and fuel.

Capabilities

1. Air-to-Air Combat: The F-22 is designed to excel in air-to-air combat, featuring exceptional maneuverability, advanced sensors, and highly integrated avionics.
2. Air-to-Ground Combat: The F-22 can carry a range of air-to-ground munitions, including precision-guided bombs and missiles.
3. Supercruise: The F-22 can maintain supersonic speeds without afterburners, providing exceptional range and endurance.
4. Advanced Sensors: The F-22's advanced sensors, including its AESA radar and advanced infrared sensors, provide exceptional situational awareness and targeting capabilities.

Operational History

The F-22 entered service in 2005 and has since been deployed in various combat and peacekeeping operations, including:

1. Operation Iraqi Freedom
2. Operation Enduring Freedom
3. Operation Inherent Resolve

Conclusion

The Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor is an exceptional fighter aircraft, boasting advanced technology, exceptional maneuverability, and unparalleled stealth capabilities. Its components, including its airframe, engines, avionics, and radar system, are highly advanced and provide exceptional performance. The F-22's capabilities, including air-to-air combat, air-to-ground combat, and supercruise, make it an invaluable asset to the USAF.

text: I've had a collapsed lung before. It happened when I was a teenager because I was tall and skinny and went through a growth spurt. My left lung developed micro tears from growing so quickly and would leak air into my chest cavity if I overexerted myself playing sports. One time my lung partially collapsed and I passed out. It was a "spontaneous pneumothorax." I ended up having to go to the hospital with an ambulance and I had multiple surgeries over the course of 2 weeks. The lungs have an enormous amount of nerves so it is extremely painful to have surgical intervention on that area. Terrible experience. Supposedly it is quite rare. 1 in 10,000. And it usually happens in tall, skinny male teenagers.

text: The "Sourtoe Cocktail" is a famous alcoholic drink served in Dawson City, Yukon, Canada, that includes a mummified human toe. The cocktail consists of a shot of whiskey (typically Yukon Jack) with a dehydrated toe included, and the only rule is to touch the toe with your lips while consuming the drink. The toe is a memento of a story from the 1920s about a rum runner who lost a toe to frostbite and preserved it in alcohol.
